21":"1421","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1409":"1409","1419":"1419","1417":"1417","1405":"1405","Gisburn, Yorkshire, England":"Gisburn, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lister","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dyer of cloth, Middle English <i>li(te)ster</i>, a derivative of Middle English <i>lit(t)en</i> (Old Norse <i>lita</i>) ‘to dye’. This term was used principally in East Anglia and northern and eastern England (areas of Scandinavian settlement), and to this day the surname is found principally in these regions, especially in Yorkshire."],"variants":[{"name":"Lester","meanings":["English: habitational name from Leicester, which is recorded as <i>Ligeraceastre</i> in the 10th century. The placename derives from an Old English folk name <i>Legore</i> ‘the dwellers by the river Legor (a lost river name)’ + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Lestre in Normandy.","English and Scottish: variant of   Lister  ."]},{"name":"Lyster","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Lister  .","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Ljøsta in Romsdal, probably derived from Old Norse <i>ljóstr</i> ‘fishing spear, leister’.","Danish: nickname originally from Bornholm, derived from a word for a fishing tackle for catching eel."]},{"name":"Lidster","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dyer, Middle English<i>litster</i> (see   Lister  )."]},{"name":"Litster","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dyer, Middle English<i>litster</i> (see   Lister  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Lister was born about 1404, in Gisburn, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Lister, was 35 and his mother, Isabel De Bolton, was 31. He married Miss Nayte in 1424, in Wakefield St Mary, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"ABT 1404–Deceased":"umbes 1404–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1400–1452":"1400–1452","1404–Male":"1404–Surnud","1409–Male":"1409–Surnud","1410–1434":"1410–1434","1415–Male":"1415–Surnud","1417–Female":"1417–Surnud","1419–Female":"1419–Surnud","1421–Female":"1421–Surnud","1423–Female":"1423–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1432–Male":"1432–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1370–1434":"1370–1434","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","ABT 1404":"umbes 1404","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1423":"1423","1434":"1434","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1421":"1421","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","1409":"1409","1419":"1419","1417":"1417","1405":"1405","Gisburn, Yorkshire, England":"Gisburn, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1404–Deceased":"noin 1404–Kuollut","1396–Male":"1396–Kuollut","1400–1452":"1400–1452","1404–Male":"1404–Kuollut","1409–Male":"1409–Kuollut","1410–1434":"1410–1434","1415–Male":"1415–Kuollut","1417–Female":"1417–Kuollut","1419–Female":"1419–Kuollut","1421–Female":"1421–Kuollut","1423–Female":"1423–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1432–Male":"1432–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1370–1434":"1370–1434","1374–Female":"1374–Kuollut","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","ABT 1404":"noin 1404","1370":"1370","1415"